[The full references for the summarized findings reported above are:
P Dietz, A Jambai, JT Paweska et al. Epidemiology and risk factors for Ebola virus infection in Sierra Leone - 23 May 2014 - 31 Jan 2015. Clin Infect Dis. (2015) (http://cid.oxfordjournals.org/content/early/2015/07/14/cid.civ568.short)
Abstract. [edited]
Background. Sierra Leone has the largest number of Ebola cases ever reported. Trends in laboratory-confirmed Ebola virus infection, symptom presentation and risk factors have not been fully described.
Methods.â€ƒEbola cases during 23 May 2014 through 31 Jan 2015 are presented by geography, demographics and risk factors for all persons who had laboratory-confirmed Ebola virus infection. Ebola virus infection (EVD) was identified by Ebola virus specific RT-PCR-based testing.
Results. During the study period, 8056 people had laboratory-confirmed EVD. The median age of cases was 28 years; 51.7 per cent were female. Common symptoms included 90.4 per cent fever, 88.3 per cent fatigue, 87.0 per cent loss of appetite, 77.9 per cent headache, 73.7 per cent joint pain, 71.2 per cent vomiting, and 70.6 per cent diarrhea. Among confirmed cases, 47.9 per cent reported having had contact with a suspected case or sick person, 25.5 per cent reported having attended a funeral, 66.2 per cent of whom reported touching the body. EVD incidence was highest during November 1-30, 2014, at 7.5 per 100,000 population per week, and decreased to 2.1 per week during January 1-31, 2015. Between 23 May and 30 Aug 2014, 2 districts had the highest incidence of 3.8 and 7.0 per 100 000 population per week which decreased over 97 per cent by 1-31 Jan 2015. In comparison, the districts that include the capital city reported a 10-fold increase in incidence per week during the same time periods. Conclusions. Almost half of EVD cases in Sierra Leone reported physical contact with a person ill with EVD or a dead body, highlighting prevention opportunities.

P Anti, M Owusu, O Agbenyega. Human-Bat Interactions in Rural West Africa Emerg Inf Dis.2015. 21 (8) - August 2015 (http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/21/8/14-2015_article)
Abstract [edited]
Because some bats host viruses with zoonotic potential, we investigated human-bat interactions in rural Ghana during 2011-2012. Nearly half (46.6 per cent) of respondents regularly visited bat caves; 37.4 per cent had been bitten, scratched, or exposed to bat urine; and 45.6 per cent ate bat meat. Human-bat interactions in rural Ghana are frequent and diverse.

KA Lindblade, F Kateh, TK Nagbe. Decreased Ebola Transmission after Rapid Response to Outbreaks in Remote Areas, Liberia, 2014. Emerg Inf Dis. 2015. 21 (10)--October 2015 (http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/21/10/15-0912_article)
Abstract [edited]
We measured the reproduction number before and after interventions were implemented to reduce Ebola transmission in 9 outbreaks in Liberia during 2014. We evaluated risk factors for secondary cases and the association between patient admission to an Ebola treatment unit (ETU) and survival. The reproduction number declined 94 per cent from 1.7 (95 per cent CI 1.1-2.6) to 0.1 (95 per cent CI 0.02-0.6) after interventions began. The risk for secondary infections was 90 per cent lower for patients admitted to an ETU (risk ratio 0.1, 95 per cent CI 0.04-0.3) than for those who died in the community. The case-fatality rate was 68 per cent (95 per cent CI 60-74), and ETU admission was associated with a 50 per cent reduction in death (hazard ratio 0.5, 95 per cent CI 0.4-0.8). Isolation and treatment of Ebola patients had the dual benefit of interrupting community transmission and improving survival. - Mod.LK]

