17 Jul 2015: Chatham House, Royal Institute of International Affairs: Ebola report misses mark on international health regulations http://www.chathamhouse.org/expert/comment/ebola-report-misses-mark-international-health-regulations#sthash.AZ0BCLWP.dpuf

17 Jul 2015: Medecins Sans Frontieres: Ebola crisis update - 17 Jul 2015
http://www.msf.org/article/ebola-crisis-update-17-Jul-2015
[Medecins Sans Frontieres: Ebola in West Africa - "We must finish the job"
For the week ending 12 Jul 2015:
Guinea: Active chains of transmission persist in Conakry, Boke and Forecariah each week. There were 12 to 18 cases. In the past 3 weeks, approximately 25 percent of positive cases were identified after death in their communities. In MSF's new Nongo facility, patients have the option to receive plasma donated by survivors of Ebola, which, after a trial enrolling 101 patients over the past few months, has been shown to produce no ill effects. The results of plasma's efficacy are not yet publicly available but hopefully will be released by the researchers in the coming weeks. In response to the recent outbreak in Boke in northern Guinea, MSF opened an Ebola management centre on 3 Jul 2015.

Sierra Leone: There were 14 new cases in the past week. Freetown has experienced an increase in cases; 10 confirmed new cases in the Western Area. MSF's maternity Ebola management center has also started to accept non-pregnant suspect and confirmed women patients (6 patients currently admitted). The country continues to be plagued by lack of its own health-care workers.

Vaccines
------------
15 Jul 2015: 2 new Ebola vaccine trials begin in Europe, Africa
http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/68567800491d48b38da3dd083fa4ce14/-
[Two new Ebola vaccine trials began on Wed [15 Jul 2015] with volunteers in Britain, France and Senegal getting "prime-boost" immunizations developed by Bavarian Nordic, GlaxoSmithKline and Johnson & Johnson.

The mid-stage, or Phase II, trials are designed primarily to test the vaccines' safety but will also assess whether they provoke an immune response against the deadly virus. ...more]

17 Jul 2015 Ghana: Hohoe welcomes Ebola vaccine trial
http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/health/Hohoe-welcomes-Ebola-vaccine-trial-369169
[Residents of Hohoe have debunked rumours that they were against the trial of Ebola vaccine in the municipality and say they only requested education on the trial vaccine.]

18 Jul 2015 Ghana: We were not told to halt Ebola vaccine trial - FDA [Federal Drug Authority, Ghana]
http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/We-were-not-told-to-halt-Ebola-Vaccine-trial-FDA-369485
[The Chief Executive of the Food and Drugs Authority, Huudu Mogtari, on Thu 16 Jul 2015, appeared before the Privileges Committee of Parliament and told members the Authority has not received any official communication from the Ministry of Health (MOH) to halt the Ebola vaccine trail. According to Mr. Mogtari, the Authority became aware of MOH's suspension of the project through the media, noting the action was contrary to laid-down procedures.]

15 Jul 2015 UK: Oxford University performs 2nd phase of experimental Ebola vaccine trial
http://www.news-medical.net/news/20150715/Oxford-University-performs-second-phase-of-experimental-Ebola-vaccine-trial.aspx
[Oxford University doctors and scientists are performing the 2nd phase of clinical studies of an experimental Ebola vaccine regimen. The study is part of the EBOVAC2 project, a collaborative program involving the University of Oxford, French Institute of Health and Medical Research (INSERM) as project coordinator, London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine (LSHTM), Le Centre Muraz (CM), Inserm Transfert (IT) and the Janssen Pharmaceutical Companies of Johnson & Johnson (Janssen).

The EBOVAC2 project is funded under a grant from the European Commission's Innovative Medicine Initiative Ebola+ program, which was launched in response to the Ebola virus disease outbreak. The EBOVAC2 project aims to assess the safety and immunogenicity of a novel prime boost preventative vaccine regimen against Ebola Virus Disease (EVD). The Phase II study aims to recruit more than 600 healthy adult volunteers in the UK and France. ...more]

15 Jul 2015 UK: Ebola vaccines trialed in Oxford now being used in Africa
http://www.thisisoxfordshire.co.uk/news/13419846._/
[Ebola vaccinations that were trialed in Oxford are now being given to people under threat in Africa. A hospital in Dakar, Senegal, has started immunizing patients from the virus, which has killed more than 11 000 people on the African continent. The 2 vaccines being used in the clinical trial were tested on human subjects at Oxford University's Jenner Institute last year [2014]. The 1st vaccination helps produce an initial immune response to the disease, and the 2nd vaccine helps the body to continue fighting the disease. ...more]

15 Jul 2015 USA: Broomfield firm Crystal Diagnostics steps into Ebola rapid test market joins neighbor Corgenix Medical Corp on short list
http://www.denverpost.com/business/ci_28489627/broomfield-firm-crystal-diagnostics-steps-into-ebola-rapid
[Just 4 companies worldwide are cleared to trial their quick tests for the deadly Ebola virus, and Crystal Diagnostics hopes to soon join its Broomfield neighbor Corgenix Medical Corp. on that short list.

When Corgenix's ReEBOV product became the 1st rapid Ebola test to receive the World Health Organization's blessing this year [2015], it was among fewer than 20 Ebola-related products submitted for the agency's assessment. Now Crystal Diagnostics, which developed a liquid crystal-based commercial product to test for pathogens in food, is adapting its device to test for diseases such as the Ebola virus. ... Crystal Diagnostics' test was successful in detecting a live-virus sample in less than 20 minutes. (Byline: Alicia Wallace)]

Research
--------
19 Jul 2015: Key protein pathways critical to Ebola virus can be blocked, according to new study
http://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/296939.php
[Scientists started their research efforts with the premise that the virus is essentially nothing without a cell. Using a newly developed statistical algorithm designed especially to prioritize the results of siRNA screens, and further computational analysis, scientists discovered 2 networks of biochemical reactions that seemed particularly critical for the virus to enter the cells - the PI3 kinase (phosphoinositide 3-kinase inhibitor) pathway and the CAMK2(calcium/calmodulin-dependent protein kinase II beta - human) pathway. There are drugs currently available to block both pathways, and researchers decided to continue on to see if they would interfere with the Ebola infection of cells. They tested both the virus pseudo-types and the Ebola Zaire virus. Researchers found that virus titers for the real Ebola virus dropped by 65 percent when the PI3 kinase inhibitor was stopped. More promising, when the CAMK2 function was blocked, the Ebola virus "stopped dead."]

19 Jul 2015: New cartoon video demystifies Ebola
http://www.huffingtonpost.com/georgianne-nienaber/new-cartoon-video-demysti_b_7797046.html
[Produced by Global Health Media, in collaboration with the International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies, UNICEF (United Nations Children's Fund), Yoni Goodman.]

